<dl id="n33284b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n33" href="#n33284b">N33 (VI.B.4)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n33all.htm#n33284b"> 284(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ~ 1. soap = 7 bars ~ <small>Not cancelled</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n33284b"><li>FW 415.04f </li><li><a href="../../flex/pC/lexpC.htm#n33284b">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/pC/l39pC.htm#n33284b">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n33284b">MS Yale 9.6-1v</ms> </li><li>JJA 57:342 <a name="pCd4" href="../../ff/fdra/pda.htm#pCd4">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/pC/pCd4.htm#n33284b">Draft: III&sect;1C.4</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">And when we are tempted to feel impressed with our own importance, we have only to remember that chemists recently discovered that the average man is made up of <mark>enough fat for seven bars of soap</mark>, enough lime to whitewash a chicken coop, enough sugar to fill a shaker, enough iron to make a small nail, enough sulphur to rid a dog of fleas, enough magnesium for a small dose, enough potassium to fire a toy cannon, enough phosphorus for a box of matches, and a couple of buckets of water. You probably couldn&apos;t get a dollar for the lot on the open market. <small> S.N.B. &ldquo;The Chemist&apos;s Magic&rdquo; <a name="PSjun26" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#PSjun26"><cite title="source">Popular Science</cite></a> (June 1926) 2</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: In text with italian <i>bolle de sapone</i>, soap bubbles. </mm> </dd></dl>
